    "experience": "Online Assessment (OA) : It consisted of three sections: \n\nData Structures & Algorithms (25 minutes) : \n\nOne coding problem was provided. \nProblem Overview: \nGiven a list of integers representing a stack of elements (from left to right), the goal was to organize them into groups \nbased on the following rules: Start with the left-most element and place it into a new group. \nFrom the remaining elements on the right, select the first element strictly less than the last added element in the group \nand add it. Repeat until no more elements can be added to the current group. Remove all grouped elements from the \noriginal list and repeat until all elements are grouped. \nReturn the list of all groups formed. \nDifficulty: Easy \n\nCS Fundamentals (20 minutes) : \n\n10 multiple-choice questions covering Operating Systems, Computer Networks, DBMS and Object-Oriented \nProgramming. \nDifficulty: Easy. \n\nAptitude & Quantitative Ability (20 minutes) : \n\n10 questions, with calculations and reasoning-based problems. \nDifficulty: Moderate to Difficult (lengthy in nature). \nShortlist Outcome: Out of all participants, 15 candidates were shortlisted for interviews. \n\nTechnical Round 1 (~50 minutes) : \n\nBegan with introductions and a brief discussion about the Online Assessment.The interviewer opened up my github and \nprojects, which were listed on the resume. Subsequent questions were asked from each of the projects as well as the \nprojects on Github. Extensive Questions about various coding profiles. Focused heavily on Computer Networks, DBMS, \nOOPS, and Operating Systems, with conceptual deep-dives.In-depth discussion on resume-listed projects, including: \nTech stack used and reasons for its selection. \nProject architecture and implementation details. \nCore Computer Science topics covered: \nVirtual Methods – Implementation and use cases. \nBasic Linux commands for file listing. \nNetworking concepts such as how ping works, BGP , and ARP . \nMulti Threading. \nDifference between compiler and interpreter. \nEach question was followed by deeper, conceptual cross-questions.Interview style was structured but friendly, focusing \non thorough understanding of fundamentals and project depth.  \nShortlist Outcome: Out of 15 candidates shortlisted for Round 1, 5 candidates were shortlisted for Technical Round 2 and \nHR Round. \n\nTechnical Round 2 (~1 hour 20 minutes) : \n\nSimilar in structure to Round 1 but with a new panel.Focused heavily on Computer Networks and Operating Systems, \nwith conceptual deep-dives.One DSA Problem: Multi-source BFS based problem. You had to explain the time and space \ncomplexity of the code. You were provided with A4 sheets and a pen, to write up the solution and explain your approach.I \nwas asked why BFS was used instead of DFS for the problem. They also asked what the time complexity would be if \nDijkstra’s algorithm had been used instead, and whether that would have been a better approach than the one I had \nprovided. The interviewers were satisfied with my response. \nThe DSA problem was as follows: \nIn a city represented as a 2D grid, there are several dark stores, houses, and obstacles. Your task is to determine the \nminimum time it takes for goods from any dark store to reach each house. Goods can only travel through empty cells, \nand cannot pass through obstacles or houses. However, they can be delivered to houses by reaching an adjacent cell \n(up, down, left, or right). Your job is to compute the minimum time required for goods from any dark store to reach each \nhouse in the grid. \n\nExample theoretical questions: \nWhat is a proxy and why is it used? \nTCP vs UDP – Advantages of one over the other. \nHow does DNS work? \nQuestions were designed to test the problem-solving approach and technical thought process. A puzzle was asked to be \nsolved, which was as follows: \nYou are given 10 coins consisting of 5 of them are heads up and the remaining are tails up. You are blindfolded and you \naren’t able to make out which coin is head/tails. You have to assemble two stacks of coins, each consisting of five coins, \nsuch that the number of heads in both stacks are the same. You are allowed to flip coins any number of times to achieve \nthe goal. \nI had 30 seconds to solve the puzzle. I quickly came up with a solution and explained my approach to the interviewers, \nwho were satisfied with it. This marked the end of the interview. \n\nHR Round (~40 minutes) : \n\nStandard HR-format discussion covering: \nIntroduction and resume review. \nStrengths and key achievements. \nLocation preference. \nUnderstanding of the role after technical interviews. \nInteraction was conversational and straightforward. You may ask questions at the end of each round.",
    "prepTips": "Strong preparation in Core CS Fundamentals and project-specific knowledge is essential. \nThey are looking for a well rounded person with extensive experience in competitive programming/DSA as well strong in \nCore CS Fundamentals. Thorough clarity on reasoning behind technical choices is valued. \n\nCoding questions tested both algorithm design and implementation speed. \nThe process was well-structured, and interviewers maintained a professional, approachable demeanor throughout. \nBe confident about your answer and try to be straight forward with your answers. \nIf you use a term in your answer, be sure to be well-versed in related matters.",
