    "experience": "OA (08/08/2025) : \n\nIt contained 20 MCQs from CS fundamentals (C programming, DBMS, Computer Networks) and one DSA question. The \nDSA question was: You are given a list of files with some numerical priorities. You must go from left to right and in one \nstack you can only stack files in decreasing order of priority. How many total stacks will have to be made to accommodate \nall the files? (Constraints: 1 <= n <= 3 x 10^5) \n\nTechnical Round 1 (08/08/2025) : \n\nIt started off with, \"Tell me about yourself.\" I mentioned my interests and projects, among other things. Since my main \ninterest was ML, I was asked questions like, \"What is recall?\" \"Why is accuracy a bad measure?\" \"What is cosine \nsimilarity?\" and \"What are the different ways of evaluating an ML model?\" \nI had an Automatic Differentiation Python Library as a project, to which they were very interested, and asked questions \nlike how I came up with the  idea of creating such a project, how it works overall (computational graphs), etc. \nI had a project using LLMs, so they asked me about the architecture of an LLM, what word embeddings are, and how \nsimilarities between words are measured. Another project of mine used FastAPI, so they asked why I used FastAPI and \nthen moved on to questions about async/await, what threading is, how to do threading in Python, and how it's different \nfrom async/await. I was able to answer all of them correctly. \nThen they moved on to Computer Networks, asking about proxies, whether IP addresses can be the same, what happens \nwhen you type a link into the browser, etc. \nAt last, they asked a DSA question: Given a list of nodes of a binary tree and an online query function isAncestor(a, b) \nwhich returns whether a is an ancestor of b, I had to reconstruct the entire tree.I first came up with a brute-force solution, \nand they asked for its time complexity. I wasn't asked to optimize it further or code the solution. \nFinally, they asked if I had any questions. I asked about what projects are given during the internship, what languages are \nused or preferred, etc. \n\nHR Round (08/08/2025): \n\nI was immediately called for the HR round and told that I was selected for technical round 2. This round began by asking \nabout the online assessment, specifically whether I found it easy or hard. I told her it was easy, so she asked why I \nthought that, and asked about my coding profiles (I have Codeforces and CodeChef). Other questions followed, like: \n\"Why did you apply here?\", \"Do you think you will be a good fit for the role and why?\", \"What are your biggest \nachievements?\", \"How do you feel college is different from school?\", \"What have you learned in your two years of \ncollege?\", \"What do you do outside of academics?\", \"What challenges have you faced when working in a group?\", etc. \nThe round was more like a discussion than an interview. \n\nTechnical Round 2 (09/08/2025): \n\nThis round immediately started with a DSA question: You are given an array of numbers and a value k, and for all \nwindows of length k in order from beginning to end, you have to return the element which appears the maximum number \nof times for each window. I was also asked to code the solution (in any language of choice, I chose Python). \nThen they asked what rate limiters are, why they are used and how I would implement one from scratch. I mentioned \nusing Redis with a defined timeout, so they started talking about Redis, what it is and why it's used. I was then asked to \ndesign it without using the timeout feature. \nThey then moved to fundamental Python questions (my main expertise is Python), like: \"What is a decorator and why is it \nused?\", \"Create a decorator to measure the time taken by a function to run.\", \"What is perf_counter?\", \"What are *args \nand **kwargs?\", \"What is GIL and why is it even applied?\". I was asked about event loops and system calls. \nThe very last question was, \"What are database indexes and why are they used?\". I mentioned B-trees, so they asked \nme to draw and explain the structure of a B-tree, which I was able to show correctly, and the interview ended.",
    "prepTips": "1) Focus on topics like Computer Networks, Operating Systems, Concurrency besides just DSA, as these are asked \nrigourously. \n2) Come prepared to implement things from scratch, so read the internal workings of everything on your resume well.",
