    "experience": "The drive begins with the OA round. It is a 1-hr round with 2 questions. Due to lack of time, I was able to only complete 1 \nproblem completely, and for the other I had to come up with a solution that intentionally does not handle some cases but \nshould finish most (if I tried to finish the second problem with a general solution, I would not have been able to submit it). \nBoth the problems passed the visible test cases, but the second problem \"should not\" pass all the hidden ones. This \nround had questions from general graphs, DSU, DP , Segment trees and recursion. After a few days, the shortlist came. I \nwas selected for the interviews. \n\nI had my 2 interviews on 2 consecutive days. Both were mentioned to be eliminative.  \nIn the first round, I joined and was asked to introduce myself. I did so. My interviewer asked about what project I was \ndoing at that time, not necessarily the ones in my resume. I mentioned about the chess app I was building. This took \nabout 5 minutes. Then, We went to the coding problem. The problem was a simple BFS problem with corrupted node \nhandling. I did so. For the follow-up, I was asked to asked to query about the distance in the graph and she added more \nconditions. I implemented it. Then she asked me, how I would find critical nodes which I should backup in case more \nnodes get corrupted. I explained her the process of Tarjan's algorithm. She looked satisfied. I asked if I had to code it, she \nsaid No. All this took 20 minutes. Since time was still left, she brought a 3rd question, this was also BFS, but I had to \nformulate the graph first with a condition (basically a BFS to make the graph) and then another BFS to solve. This was \nthe 35th minute mark. After this, we were simple having a chat about life at Google. The interview was around 40-45 \nminutes. \n\nA few hours after the interview, I received a mail from google saying that I progressed to round 2. And it was scheduled \nfor the next day. \n\nThe next day, I joined the interview. There was no introduction. The interviewer asked my name and we straight away \nwent for the coding question. The question was: \nGiven 3 sorted integer arrays a, b, c of length n each and an integer D, find the number of tuples (i, j, k) such that: \n| a[i] - b[j] | <= D \n| b[j] - c[k] | <= D \n| c[k] - a[i] | <= D \n\nI mentioned that brute force of O(n^3) ofcourse exists. Since the array was monotonic, we could use binary search or two \npointers. If we fix the array with the smaller number (say a) and create windows in b and c for the permissible indices, we \ncan simple multiply number of indices in those windows; then do the same keeping b as the smaller, followed by c. \n(Noticing the pointer to the middle value of the triplet is irrelevant, just the difference between largest and smallest needs \nto be <= D) There was some overcounting in the smaller side for handling the fixing of smaller array, which I noticed while \ncoding itself and fixed. The final solution was O(n) time and O(1) space. It had been 35 minutes of the interview. \n\nThe interviewer asked me to convert the fixing of the 3 cases (a, b or c first) into a single function. I did so. I used an \nincrement trick to handle the assymetries of the 3 fixed to take into account overcount of cases where a[i] = b[j] or b[j] = \nc[k] or c[k] = a[i] in fixing the lower bound. The interviewer asked me to explain why the two-pointers/sliding-window \napproach gave O(n) time. I explained the concept of amortization. The interviewer seemed satisfied. \nThere was hardly any time left. We chatted for a couple of minutes, and the 45 minutes was over. \n\nThe next day, in the afternoon, I received a message saying I was shortlisted.",
    "prepTips": "Start with DSA early. This is more-or-less the only thing questioned in the interviews. Cover all the topics and implement \nthem. The questions are never \"implement quicksort\" but something that requires you to first come up with the algorithm. \n\nAlso, the interviews are taken in a text editor made by google with no autocomplete, not even bracket completion. So, I \nwould recommend, before the interview practice coding in notepad or google docs.",
    "additionalNotes": "Do not panic. The interviewers are very friendly. You can ask them about anything you want. If you are unfamiliar with \na topic tell them. Often times, they might even give hints.",
