    "experience": "In the OA there were 2 DSA questions and we had 60 minutes to solve it.The first question was based on graph and can \nbe solved using connected components only. the second question was given a integer n, find number of palindromes <=n \nsuch that ith digit occurs i number of times (like if 2 occurs in the palindrome it should occur exactly 2 times).It could be \nsolved by generating all possibilities using bfs but during the OA i was not able to fully optimize the solution.The question \nwas for n upto 1e17 and my solution was correct for n upto 1e13 only  \n\nThe interview took place on Google Meet, and we used Interview Docs(similar to Google Docs but had syntax \nhighlighting for code) The interviewer began by introducing herself and then asked me to introduce myself. Then she \nverbally explained the question. The problem was \"given a undirected unweighted graph and a list of nodes which \ncontains the nodes with a data center , my task was to find a node in the graph in which if we make a new data center \nthen it will be furthest from all the other data centers\" - initially the question felt a bit ambiguous so I asked the interviewer \nfor clarification and came to a conclusion that the question was simply find a node such that the minimum distance  of it \nfrom any of the data centers is maximum .Then I explained my brute force and its time complexity and she asked me to \noptimize it, the optimal solution was using multisource bfs from all the initially given data centers to find our answer . I told \nher the optimal solution and the she asked me to dry run it and finally to code it. Then she followed it up with the question \n\"what if the graph was weighted insted\" , the solution to this was to use multisource dijkstra instead of bfs, I told her that \nand finally coded up this solution as well, the interview ended in about 30 minutes and about 15 minutes later i got the \nemail for my second round \n\nThe second round was easier than the first round, the interviewer told me to introduce myself and then she pasted a \nquestion (she was trying to observe what is my approach when i see a question , so she asked me to go through the \nquestion myself and if i have a doubt then clarify it) the first question was given a necklace(linear) of 2*r rubies and 2*d \ndiamonds find 2 or less partitions such that we can distribute the parts of the necklace between two thieves and both of \nshould get d diamonds and r rubies .it could be solved using a sliding window of size r+d. The next question was given an \narray which contains start_time of some processes and a time t which each process takes to complete ,what is the \n\nminimum time to complete all the processes if our computer can handle c processes simultaneously.it could be solved \nusing queues. I told the optimal solutions ,dry run them on given test cases, wrote the code and mentioned time and \nspace complexity for both .Even though I got the space complexity wrong on the second question, the interviewer was \nhelpful and she guided me through the mistake. Overall the round was of 45 minutes.",
