    "experience": "In the online assessment, there were two questions: one on dynamic programming (DP) on string and another that was \nmore challenging, requiring knowledge of segment trees. I successfully solved the DP question. For the second one, I \nimplemented a brute force solution that passed the given test cases. \n\nIn the first interview, I was tasked with a room allocation problem. The goal was to allocate rooms such that most interns \ngot a room, considering that some interns wanted housemates and others didn’t. The input was provided as a vector of \nstructs, and while I was able to come up with a solution, there were a number of edge cases that added complexity. \nAlthough my code missed a few edge cases, the interviewer was understanding and gave positive feedback after I \nperformed a dry run on one of the edge cases. \n\nThe second interview involved an array problem where the objective was to find the maximum subarray sum. The catch \nwas that if arr[i] == arr[j] for i <= j, I had to compute the sum of the subarray between indices i and j. Initially, I proposed a \nbrute force solution involving multiple loops. However, when the interviewer asked me to optimize it, I quickly modified the \nKadane's algorithm with a hash map to come up with an efficient solution. The interviewer was pleased with the approach \nand didn't ask for a dry run. The interview wrapped up in 20 minutes.",
