    "experience": "I secured this opportunity through an off-campus process, without any referral involved.  \n\nAfter my resume was shortlisted, I was contacted by a recruiter. This began with an initial phone screening, where the \nrecruiter asked me to give an introduction. The conversation then moved on to a few background questions to assess my \npreparation and interests. These included how many DSA questions I had solved, which coding platforms I used, and \nwhat my CGPA was. The recruiter also asked about my primary programming language, as well as the tech stack I had \nused in my projects. I was asked to give a brief overview of one of my projects, including the technologies involved and \nthe overall goal. \n\nThe call concluded with the recruiter asking for my availability so that she could schedule the first round of technical \ninterviews. \n\nBoth interview rounds were scheduled on short notice, and I had to manage them alongside my ongoing semester \nexams. In fact, one of the rounds took place between two of my exams, which added to the pressure. Moreover, I’m \nsharing this experience after quite some time has passed, so I don’t remember the exact questions word-for-word. \n\nEach interview round focused entirely on Data Structures and Algorithms. Once the recruiter confirmed the date and time, \nI received a Google Meet link along with a shared interview document. The document is a plain, blank file with no pre-\nwritten code. During the interview, the interviewer pastes the question in front of you, and you're expected to write the \ncode from scratch. \n\nTechnical Round 1 \nThe first technical round lasted for about 45 minutes. It started with a brief self-introduction, which I kept short in order to \nmake the most of the available time. We immediately proceeded to the first question, which was based on trees. I initially \ndiscussed the brute-force approach with the interviewer, followed by the code implementation. After that, I provided an \noptimized version and explained that as well. \nThe second question was based on graphs, and followed a similar pattern of discussion, coding, and optimization. For \nboth questions, I was also asked to calculate the time and space complexity of my solutions. I also had to dry run the \nquestions to demonstrate their correctness. At the end, the interviewer gave me the opportunity to ask any questions I \nhad. Since I was quick with coding, the round was completed efficiently within the allotted time. \n\nThe next day, the recruiter informed me that I had cleared Round 1 and was selected for Technical Round 2. \n\nTechnical Round 2 \nThe second technical round was more intense and lasted for around 55 minutes, slightly longer than the usual 45-minute \nformat. The interviewer asked me three questions, covering the topics of recursion, backtracking, DP and strings. \nFor each question, I discussed both the brute-force and optimized solutions, implemented the code and clearly explained \nmy thought process. I was also asked to compute the time and space complexity for all the solutions. Since I had to work \nthrough three questions along with both brute-force and optimized approaches, the interview extended beyond the usual \ntime.  \n\nFinal Result \nAfter waiting for over 1.5 months, I was informed that I had been selected.",
    "prepTips": "Have some strong projects on your resume, along with your coding and educational achievements. \nPractice dry running your solutions to ensure they work correctly. \nLearn how to calculate the time and space complexity of your solutions. \n\nDuring the interview, actively interact with your interviewer and try to clearly explain your code and thought process.",
    "additionalNotes": "For each coding question, try to ask clarifying questions to ensure you fully understand the problem. \nTry to write comments in your code. \nUse meaningful variable and function names to make your code clean and easy to understand.",
