    "experience": "1st round : \nThe interview was conducted online via Microsoft Teams, but we had to give it from Teqip. The interviewer started by \nintroducing himself and then asked me to introduce myself and talk a bit about what I've worked with and what I have \nexperience in (if any). I introduced myself with the basics, followed by brief explanations of my projects and the tech \nstacks I've used in them. Then the Interviewer continued with a few questions about the project and moved on to CS \nfundamentals. He asked multiple questions on OOPS, DBMS, Java, DSA, and CN. He followed up on many questions \nwith further questions based on my answers and also asked some out-of-the-box questions in between. He also asked \nme to write down some queries and code snippets on a piece of paper and show them to him through the camera. Then \nhe ended the interview after asking me if I had any questions for him, to which I responded with a couple of questions \nabout the work culture and about his feedback on what I could try to work on as an interviewee. \nI was called in for the 2nd round about 15 mins after the 1st round. \n2nd round: \nThis was a proper in-person interview for me. The interviewer started by introducing himself and asked me to introduce \nmyself and my experience in the domain. He asked for much basic information like my background, where I went to \nschool, what subjects I loved in school and why I chose that stream, and how I ended up in JU. Then he started asking \nquestions on CS fundamentals (OOPS, DBMS, DSA, Java, CN). Again, there were multiple follow-up questions based \non my answers and some out-of-the-box questions. I was also asked to write down queries and code snippets on paper \nand show them. After a lot of time on these, he asked me a critical thinking question that I could not solve immediately, \nand I was given some time to think, and I could ask him as many questions as I wanted to clarify doubts. He gave me a \nhint after some time, and I solved it then. Again, the interviewer asked me if I had any further questions for him, and I \nkind of asked similar questions to those in the 1st round, after answering which the interview ended. \nWe were informed that we have to come back the next morning for a 3rd round (HR round). \n\n3rd round (HR): \nThe interview was an in-person interview again. The interviewer started by introducing himself and again asked me to \nintroduce myself a bit. He asked questions about my background, like where my hometown is, where I went to school, \nmy class 10 and 12 boards percentages, my current CGPA considering all 4 semesters, and if I have any active \nbacklogs. He also asked me how I ended up in JU and why I chose JU. Then he asked me why I want to work with \nWells Fargo, and why they should hire me. He asked me a bit about my knowledge of the company and its values. \nThen he asked me about my family background and if I am comfortable with relocating for this position in any location \nthey offer to me. After all this, he asked me if I am going to wait till the end until results are declared or whether I'll leave \nfor a class or something. The interview ended here. \nThe interviewers were very friendly, and the overall experience was very nice. All the interviews felt very conversational, \nand the interviewers were also very supportive and amenable to talk to.",
    "prepTips": "Prepare all CS fundamental topics thoroughly and have knowledge about your projects and the tech stacks used. Be ready \nto face questions beyond your knowledge and know how to react to them.",
    "additionalNotes": "Answer confidently and try to keep the interview conversational. Ask for hints or think out loud when you face a question \nthat you don't know the answer to. Let the interviewer know about your strong points if you can, through simple \nconversation.",
