    "experience": "Round 1: Online Assessment \nThe OA consisted of four sections: \n- S1: Coding: 1 question on graph algorithms (e.g., Dijkstra's, Multi-Source BFS). \n\n- S2: Verbal Aptitude: Standard verbal ability questions. \n- S3: Market Analysis: Situational judgment questions. \n- S4: Automata Section: 2 coding questions (Easy-Medium) on topics like HashMaps and Sliding Window. \nResult: 33 students were shortlisted. \nRound 2: Technical Interview 1 (Virtual) \n- Duration: 40 minutes \n- Topics Covered: \n- Projects: Discussion on my video downloading service project, with follow up questions on constraints like \nuser storage space. \n- DBMS: 3-tier architecture. \n- SQL: Write a query to find the second minimum salary. \n- OOP & Java: Method overloading vs. overriding, constructors, Java internals, and the Collection Framework. \nResult: 20-23 students advanced to the next round. \nRound 3: Technical Interview 2 (Offline) \n- Duration: 35-40 minutes \n- Topics Covered: \n- DSA: In-depth questions on the internal workings of Queue, Stack, and variations of Dijkstra's algorithm (be \nsure to mention the pros and cons of each algo that you maybe asked) \n- Core Concepts: Java/Python internal workings, memory management(few OS concepts can come in handy \nhere), multiple inheritance. \n- Version Control (Git): Concepts like merge, pull, clone, and the purpose of rebase. \nResult: 15 students were selected for the HR round. \nRound 4: HR Interview \n- Key Questions: \n- Why did you choose your university (JU)? (Know your institute's NIRF ranking). \n- Why Wells Fargo? \n- What is the function of a bank? \n- Why do banks need software engineers, and why can't they be replaced by AI? \n- Code submitted in previous technical rounds.",
    "prepTips": "Questions mentioned in the HR round can be asked in any of the rounds, so be prepared with them beforehand \nAlso check out some puzzle articles from GFG as many of my friends were asked about them(e.g. the 8 ball \nweighing problem)",
